initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: Classical convolutional neural networks have been successfully applied to image recognition in recent years. A novel extension, quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNS), uses quantum mechanisms, which enable efficient training by reducing input size from n to log2n. This study compares and implements both QCNNS and classical CNNs, evaluating their performance on three datasets: MNIST hand-written digits, Fashion MNIST, and cat/dog images. Although data augmentation, often used in classical CNNs to enhance classification, was also applied to QCNNS, surprisingly, the results showed no improvement. The authors analyze the reasons behind this outcome to broaden our understanding of quantum machine learning.

Recent years have seen the successful use of classical convolutional neural networks in image recognition. A newer approach, quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNS), utilises quantum principles to efficiently reduce input sizes from n to log2n. This investigation contrasts and integrates both QCNNS and classical CNNs, evaluating their performance across three datasets: handwritten digits, Fashion MNIST, and feline versus canine imagery. Notably, although data augmentation, a common technique used to boost classification with classical CNNs, was employed with QCNNS, the results offered no additional improvements. The authors delve into the reasons behind this result to improve the comprehension of quantum machine learning.
